\section*{Problem}

A nucleus $A$ of mass $2m$ moving with velocity $\mathbf{u}$ collides inelastically with a stationary nucleus $B$ of mass $10m$. After the collision, the nucleus $A$ travels at $90^\circ$ with the incident direction while $B$ proceeds at an angle $37^\circ$ with the incident direction. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Find the speeds of $A$ and $B$ after the collision.
    \item[(b)] What fraction of the initial kinetic energy is gained or lost due to the collision?
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Speeds of A and B after the collision}

Using the conservation of momentum, we have:

\begin{align*}
    \text{Initial momentum:} \quad & \mathbf{p}_{\text{initial}} = 2m \mathbf{u} \\
    \text{Final momentum:} \quad & \mathbf{p}_{\text{final}} = 2m \mathbf{v}_A + 10m \mathbf{v}_B
\end{align*}

Since the collision is inelastic and the angles are given, we can resolve the momentum into components:

\begin{align*}
    \text{In the x-direction:} \quad & 2m u = 10m v_B \cos 37^\circ \\
    \text{In the y-direction:} \quad & 0 = 2m v_A + 10m v_B \sin 37^\circ
\end{align*}

Solving these equations, we find the speeds $v_A$ and $v_B$.

\subsection*{(b) Fraction of initial kinetic energy gained or lost}

The initial kinetic energy $K_{\text{initial}}$ is:

\begin{align*}
    K_{\text{initial}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 2m \times u^2 = mu^2
\end{align*}

The final kinetic energy $K_{\text{final}}$ is:

\begin{align*}
    K_{\text{final}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 2m \times v_A^2 + \frac{1}{2} \times 10m \times v_B^2
\end{align*}

The fraction of kinetic energy lost is:

\begin{align*}
    \text{Fraction lost} = \frac{K_{\text{initial}} - K_{\text{final}}}{K_{\text{initial}}}
\end{align*}

Substitute the expressions for $v_A$ and $v_B$ obtained from the momentum equations to find the numerical value.

\end{document}
```

