\title{Physics Problem: Bullet and Block}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A bullet weighing 5 g is fired horizontally into a 2 kg wooden block resting on a horizontal table. The bullet is arrested within the block which moves 2 m. If the coefficient of kinetic friction between the block and the surface of the table is 0.2, find the speed of the bullet.

\section*{Solution}

First, we need to calculate the work done by the friction force as the block moves 2 m. The friction force \( f_k \) is given by:

\[
f_k = \mu_k \cdot m \cdot g
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
\mu_k &= 0.2 \quad \text{(coefficient of kinetic friction)} \\
m &= 2 \, \text{kg} \quad \text{(mass of the block)} \\
g &= 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2 \quad \text{(acceleration due to gravity)}
\end{align*}

Substituting the values, we get:

\[
f_k = 0.2 \times 2 \times 9.81 = 3.924 \, \text{N}
\]

The work done by the friction force \( W_f \) over a distance \( d = 2 \, \text{m} \) is:

\[
W_f = f_k \cdot d = 3.924 \times 2 = 7.848 \, \text{J}
\]

According to the work-energy principle, the initial kinetic energy of the system (bullet + block) is equal to the work done by the friction force:

\[
\frac{1}{2} (m + m_b) v^2 = W_f
\]

where \( m_b = 0.005 \, \text{kg} \) is the mass of the bullet and \( v \) is the initial speed of the bullet. Solving for \( v \):

\[
\frac{1}{2} (2 + 0.005) v^2 = 7.848
\]

\[
1.0025 v^2 = 7.848
\]

\[
v^2 = \frac{7.848}{1.0025}
\]

\[
v^2 \approx 7.828
\]

\[
v \approx \sqrt{7.828} \approx 2.797 \, \text{m/s}
\]

Thus, the speed of the bullet is approximately \( 2.797 \, \text{m/s} \).

\end{document}
```

